Vesicular stomatitis (VS) in Texas -- update
--------------------------------------------
The Texas Animal Health Commission (TAHC) received confirmation of 6 new cases of vesicular stomatitis (VS) in horses in Central Texas. 3 new premises are located in Bastrop County and 2 new premises are in Travis County. One new premises is located in Falls County, the 1st case reported in this county.

One premises is located 1 mile [1.6 km] east of Manchaca in Travis County
One premises is located 5 miles [8 km] west of Marlin in Falls County
One premises is located 10 miles [16 km] southeast of Bastrop in Bastrop County
One premises is located 2 miles [3.2 km] north of Bastrop in Bastrop County
One premises is located 5 miles [8 km] north of Del Valle in Travis County
One premises is located 8 miles [13 km] northwest of Bastrop in Bastrop County

To date, 42 premises in 10 Texas counties have been confirmed with VS. Affected counties include(d): Kinney, Hidalgo, San Patricio, Nueces, Jim Wells, Bastrop, Travis, Guadalupe, Val Verde, and Falls counties. 8 premises have been released from quarantine: 1 in Kinney county, 2 in Nueces county, 2 in San Patricio county, 2 in Hidalgo county and 1 in Jim Wells county.
*Case = A premises; a location*

The newly identified infected premises are currently under quarantine by the TAHC. Affected horses will be monitored by regulatory veterinarians while under quarantine. Premises are eligible for quarantine release 21 days after all lesions have healed.

For VS history and past updates, visit http://www.tahc.texas.gov/animal_health/equine/equine.html.

Several states are imposing enhanced entry requirements on Texas livestock due to VS cases in Texas. For information about these movement restrictions, contact the state or country of destination and/or visit http://www.tahc.texas.gov/news/2014StateRestrictionsOnTX_VS.pdf.

--
Communicated by:
Bonnie Ramirez
<bonnie.ramirez@tahc.state.tx.us>

